comments: Russell (MIN) initiates contact to Bane's (MEM) front with an extended hand, but the contact occurs before the start of Bane's upward shooting motion.
Morant (MEM) maintains a legal guarding position while defending Russell (MIN) on the perimeter and his drive to the basket.
Russell (MIN) does not overtly extend his leg into Morant (MEM) during his jump shot attempt and the contact is marginal.
Clarke (MEM) briefly places his hands on Edwards (MIN) as he disengages and the contact is marginal.
Vanderbilt (MIN) moves along Brooks' (MEM) path and absorbs the contact initiated by Brooks.

Clarke (MEM) has his right arm extended and inadvertently makes contact with Beverley's (MIN) head as he moves into his arm.   Contact to an opponent?s head/face can be deemed marginal when the result of a natural basketball move, provided the contact is not disproportionate or uncontrolled.
Morant (MEM) jumps forward to contest the jump shot attempt by Russell (MIN) and would avoid making contact if not for Russell extending his left leg to create the marginal contact.
Brooks (MEM) and Prince (MIN) make marginal contact with each other during the rebound and Prince loses his balance on his own.
As Beverley (MIN) receives the pass, Bane (MEM) reaches in and initiates contact to his arm that causes him to lose control of the ball.
Beverley (MIN) and Morant (MEM) make marginal contact with each other as both players go for the loose ball.
Beverley (MIN) briefly places his arm on Morant's (MEM) body during his drive toward the rim.
Brooks (MEM) commits a take foul on Edwards (MIN).
Edwards (MIN) briefly places his arm around Morant (MEM) but immediately removes it without impacting his FOM.
Anderson (MEM) commits a take foul onTowns (MIN).
Towns (MIN) and Clarke (MEM) make marginal contact as both players go for the ball.
